	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=22775><span id=Guru>SuBoneTL</span></a><br><b><span id=Guru>Guru</span></b><br><span id=notbold>93 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent [4.56]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>Mor than two years ago I started my very first character; a ranger.&nbsp;&nbsp;I knew nothing about the class at the time, I think I just liked the name.  But when I started playing, I immediately fell in love with it- Immediately after I found my way off of Kelethin, that is.  I thought it was so cool that I could find any monster I wanted just by clicking a button.  I didn't tell anyone else I could do it, because I thought it was an unfair advantage and they'd get jealous.  The more I played the ranger, the more I grew to love the lifestyle.  But as I grew in levels, I had to wonder why people laughed at rangers so much.  I had to list off everything I could, that others couldn't do, before I could get into a lot of groups.  People thought/think that rangers are merely weak warriors, with a few weak druid spells.  And to some extent, this is true, especially before ~30 when we really come into our own in the public eye.  But before that, I made a vow to myself that I was going to prove that rangers were the best class to everyone else.  I had to learn everything about my own abilities, and about everyone else's to learn how to maximize group play efficiency, and work out how dynamics in group should work between classes.  I can proudly say that I think I did that very well.  I started hearing thnigs like, "Wow.  I didn't know you guys could do that!" or "Man, M**********.  We would have been gone without those snares," or "Nice pulls!  Perfect timing, cons, and with snares/dots already on them!"  That last one was a combination of three, said by the same person in the same group:-P  But, yea.  And at 30, our melee ability is greatly enhanced.  We become damage dealers at this point, instead of ambiguously identified, multitalented, handsome tree people with great senses of humor, and sexy six-packs.  But this new damage-dealing boost is only in addition to everything we had before!  After 30-35 we started staying on par with warriors' damage output, and sometimes surpassing theirs.  We can be secondary tanks with taunts, dual-weild, spells, etc.  We're actually excellent pullers, although people don't recognize us such.  I was chosen over our monk, and bard, as main puller in many groups, on many occasions.  This wasn't before I had to show them what I could do though.  I became somewhat of a rolemodel for younger rangers, which didn't fill my head, but made me feel proud, and feel that I'd done my job.  People would ask me about our class, ask me how we fight best, and about things I'd done.We will always we prejudiced against as being weaklings, and not having any roles in groups.  This is why we must work hard to represent well.  We must be the best we can be!:-P<br>Besides our great grouping potential, we are excellent soloers as well, with our harmony, dots/dd, snare, archery (greatly underutilized), buffs, tracking, etc.  I soloed my first cyclops (29-32) at 24 in SK.  I was soloing Avocets at that time too.  With a good bow and arrows, along with spells, it doesn't end up being as inefficient time-wise as it would seem.  I used a Runed Oak at the time, was the best bow in the game back then.  That was a long time, and only one of the better soloing accoplishments achieved.  But this is just to say what is possible, and surpassable for our great class.  Ignore those meanie-heads who say Rangers are weak, have no role in group, or are silly, and show them what you can do.  Represent well, brothers/sisters!  Be safe, and have fun!  Laterz</p>&nbsp;<br>Hyden Endabrush<br>Expert Scout of the Fay</td></td></tr>
